South African Stocks: Exxaro, Massmart, Optimum Coal, Telkom

-- B y   S t e p h e n   G u n n i o n   a n d   R o b e r t   B r a n d
-- 
2011-10-17T15:38:49Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-10-17/south-african-stocks-anglo-optimum-psg-sasol-spar-telkom.html
The FTSE/JSE Africa All Share Index
declined, slumping 28.36, or 0.1 percent, to 31,095.23 by the 5
p.m. close in Johannesburg.  The following were among the most active stocks in the
South African market today.  Exxaro Resources Ltd. (EXX)  , the coal miner that exports
about 42 percent of its production, rose for a second day,
adding 2.43 rand, or 1.4 percent, to 179.53 rand. Coal export
prices at  Richards Bay ,  South Africa , the continent’s biggest
terminal for shipping the fuel, rose for the first week in six,
according to data on Bloomberg from researcher IHS McCloskey.  Massmart Holdings Ltd. (MSM)  , a South African retailer
controlled by Wal-Mart Stores Inc., snapped two days of declines
after saying sales in the first 14 weeks of the fiscal year
climbed 15 percent. The stock gained 1.05 rand, or 0.7 percent,
to 147.55 rand.  Optimum Coal Holdings (OPT)  Ltd, a coal producer, rose
the most in two months, surging 2.89 rand, or 8.5 percent, to
36.90 rand. Piruto BV, a unit of Glencore International Plc,
increased its stake in Optimum to 28.46 percent from 25.66
percent, the company said in a stock exchange statement today.  Pinnacle Technology Holdings Ltd. (PNC)  , a supplier of
computer and networking equipment, gained 7 cents, or 0.7
percent to 10.07 rand, the highest closing price on record.
Pinnacle agreed to buy the 49 percent it doesn’t own of Explix
Business Solutions (Pty.) Ltd. for 3.5 million rand.  PSG Group Ltd. (PSG)  , an investment holding company
focused on the financial sector, increased to its highest in 11
weeks, advancing 56 cents, or 1.2 percent, to 48 rand. The value
of the group’s investments rose 12 percent to 52.34 rand per
share in the six months to Aug. 31 from the year earlier period,
it said in a regulatory filing.  Rare Holdings Ltd. (RAR)  , which makes pipes and valves,
dropped 1 cent, dropped 7.7 percent, to 12 cents, a four-month
low, after reporting a loss of 66.9 million rand from continuing
operations for the year ended June 30.  Taste Holdings Ltd. (TAS)  , a restaurant franchise
holder, climbed to the highest since May 2007 after saying it’s
in talks about buying The Fish & Chip Co, which has more than
160 franchised outlets. The shares surged 10 cents, or 7.1
percent, to 1.50 rand.  Telkom South Africa Ltd. (TKG SJ), the South African fixed-
line operator controlled by the government, had its biggest one-
day decline in more than two weeks, shedding 83 cents, or 2.5
percent, to 32.02 rand. The Congress of South African Trade
Unions, the country’s largest labor federation, said it opposes
plans by Telkom to sell a 20-percent stake to KT Corp. of  South
Korea .  The  Spar Group Ltd. (SPP)  , the South African food and
liquor retailer, advanced 1.60 rand, or 1.7 percent, to 97.50
rand. A strike at the group’s KwaZulu-Natal warehouse has not
significantly disrupted deliveries to its stores,  Business
Report  said, citing Chief Executive Officer Wayne Hook.  To contact the reporter on this story:
